{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_endive_ver02/data/sn86063811/00279558376/1937092201/0463.xml":{"full_text":"WEATHER\nh'jtir tonight and Thursday with\nlittle change in temperature.\n\u00a9he cEtmrs\nLargest Daily Circulation of Any Newspaper in Morth Carolina in Proportion to Population\nGOOD AFTERNOON\nMuuolini iayi all hi* thoughts\nare bent o\u00bbN preventing war. Not\nbent, Duce, just plain warped.\nVOL- 56\u2014No. 227\nHENDERSONV1LLE, N. C., WEDNESDAY, SEPTEMBER 22, 1937\nSINGLE COPIES, FIVE CENTS\nFrance Warns Italy To End Spanish Aid\nWOULD ALLOW\nVOLUNTEERS\nCROSS BORDER\n:rench Stand Given by\nDelbos to Italian Min\nister to Switzerland\nIEBELS THREATENING\nANTI-FRENCH ACTS\nGENEVA. Sept. 22. (UP) The\nation became tense\ni> Fra-v v ttened to open her\nh i I. va' st volunteers to\nrr :r Uenito Mussolini\nand material to\nto rebtrls.\nr V >ti-r Vvon Delbos\na I-a sending more\nr a talk with the Italian\nSi itwriaad.\nEBELS THREATEN\nORDER REPRISALS\nGAINST FRANCE\nPARIS. S\u00abpt. 22. (VP)\u2014Major\nliian Troncoso, Spanish rebel\nimmander who was arrested by\nr*nch secret police in connection\nita the attempted hijacking of a\nivalist submarine. was removed\nI jail n Bayonne last night\nb*n 1,000 rebel troops threat\nled to cross the border and ex\nt npiiful*.\nSquadrons of French mobile\nlaid? were rushed to the Pyren\nis frontier after Troncoso had\nId authorities that his arrest\nL< \"a veritable declaration of\nir on Nationalist Spain.\"\nTroncoso .right-hand man of\npuntent Generalissimo Francisco t\nrtneo. was -aid by police to have\n*n involved not only in the at\nmpted hijacking of the Loyalist\nboat C-2 at Brest but in the\nrrorism of \"Les Cagoulards,\"\nsnch secret society of hooded\nM.\nThe rebel major, military com\nandant of Irun, opposite Hen\nye on the Franco-Spanish fron\n\u25bar. said that unless he was re\ni*d immediately and allowed to\nturn to Spain, the French con\nat San Sebastian. J. E. Les\nartres. would be seized as a hos\nThe frontier was sealed on both\nws of the muddy Bidassoa river\nR night and indignation ran\nph. particularly in Irun.\nTh* 1000 insurgent troops, red\nWed requetes of Franco's mon\ndivisions, were reported to\nagreed to break through the\n[rocades at the international\n}dge and storm the French com\nissariat at Hendaye unless their\n\u2022dtr is released.\nTroncoso arrived at Bayonne at\nill rt* m' anc' was P'*ce<^ >n\n-a Chagrin prison. He was to\n1 ^xen into court today to hear\ncnarj^s against him.\n\"\"confirmed report from\nJean de Lux <aid that Gen\n\u25a0wmo Franco had renounced\nwtcoso.\nAnother report from insurgent\nLr <a'^ franco regarded his\nSlants arrest as \"the most\n7** 'ncident with the French\nrnment since the beginning\nI the war.'\nCE IS GOING TO\nN TO CONFER\nHITLER AGAIN\n*OME. Sept. 22. (UP)\u2014 Pre\nBenito Mussolini will leave\nFriday for Berlin to con\n*ith Fuehrer Adolf Hitler and\nthe Reich's army maneu\nin Mecklenburg, it was an\n_ Jiced early today.\nI'l Ducf will be accompanied by\nMini-'er Count Galeazzo\nn-law; Dino Aldi\nf mynnill minister; Achille\nF*^,- secretary of the Fascist\npcd council; and Mussolini's pri\nr* .-a y. (Kcaldo Sebas\nvisit with Hit\nI announced.\nI jC- will k\u00ab> to Mecklenburjr on\nS 26, to attend the\nami-. After the maneuvers\n*\"l return to Berlin and will\nfftr Rome Sept. 29.\nflVIC CHORAL\nCLUB TO MEET\nJV rvju'ar rehearsal of the\njJ**sonville Civic Choral club\nC?.* held Thursday niffbt at\n\u25a0J!\u00ae clock in the Presbyterian\n\u25a0J**\" house. AH members are\nKr* to report promptly at that\nr* ,or an important rehearsal.\nBaptist Leaders Here for Revival\nDR. TIMMERMAN\nMR. KEITH\nA ten-day series of revival meetings will open tonight at 7:30 o'clock\nat the First Baptist church. Rev. N. D. Timmerman, pastor of the\nFirst Baptist church, Clarksdale, Miss., will do the preaching twice\ndaily, and E. S. Keith, assistant pastor of Tabernacle Baptist church,\nHazel Park, Detroit, Mich., will direct the singing.\nWOODRING TELLS LEGION IT\nMUST WORK FOR U. S. PEACE\nBAPTISTS WILL\nOPEN REVIVAL\nDr. Timmerman to Speak\nHere Twice Daily, Begin\nning Tonight\nA series of revival meetings, to\ncontinue for ten days, will open\nat the First Baptist church here\ntonight at 7:30 o'clock, with the\nRev. N\\ D. Timmerman, D. D.,\npastor of the First Baptist church\nof Clarksdale, Miss., speaking\ntwice each day during the revival\nperiod.\nRev. Timmerman is a strong,\nforceful speaker and brings an\nintellectual and practical message\nOB the fMMl, Rev. B. E. Wall,\npastor of the church, said this\nmorning. Preparations have been\nunderway for some time for the\nservices by members of the con\ngregation, and large congrega\ntions are expected to attend the\nmeeting. Rev. Wall today ex\ntended a special message to mem\nbers of other denominations to\nattend the services.\nAssisting Dr. Timmerman in\nthe services will be E. D. Keith,\nassistant pastor of the Tabernacle\nBaptist church of Hazel Park,\nDetroit, Mich., who will direct the\nmusic for the special services. In\naddition to being a fine soloist, I\nMr. Keith is also well known as\na director of congregational sing\nin*'\nDuring the ten-day period, ser\nvices will be held each morning\nat 10 o'clock and each evening at\n7:30 o'clock. At the evening ser\nvices each department of the Sun\nday school will meet separately\nat 7:30 for their services, and at\n7:45 all will gather in the church\nauditorium for the evening ser\nvice. All Sunday school pupils, of\nficers and teachers are urged to\nattend their respective meetings.\nHARPER RITES\nSET THURSDAY\nMiss Urana Harper Passes\nTuesday Night at Fruit\nland Home\nMiss Urana Harper, 36, daugh\nter of Mr. and Mrs. K. H. Har\nper. died at the home of her par\nents in the Fruitland section last\nnight at 10:55 o'clock.\nThe funeral services will be\nheld on Thursday afternoon at 2\no'clock at Moore's Grove Metho\ndist church. Services will be con\nducted by the Revs. R. P. and\nQuay Corn, and burial will fol\nlow in the cemetery there.\nBALL GAMES FREE\nTOKYO, Sept. 22. (UP)\u2014The\nBaseball association, hoping to\nsuntain interest in baseball,, last\nnight abolished admission, fees to\n1 all games because of declining at\ntendance as a result of the war.\nGreen Pledges Resources\nto Fight Communism,\nOther Alien Ideas\nNEW YORK. Sept. 22. (UP)\nSecretary of War Harry Wood\nring today told the American Le\ngionnaires they must be alert to\ncombat forces which would carry\nthe United States into another\nwar. Woodring pledged that the\ngovernment would work unceas\ningly for peace in America.\nGeneral Frank T. Hines, federal\nadministrator of veterans affairs,\nalso spoke and promised that the\ngovernment would not attempt to\nbring about economies at the ex\npense of veterans.\nLos Angeles was selected for\nnext year's convention.\nGREEN PLEDGES AID TO\nKEEP DOWN RADICALISM\nNEW YORK. Sept. 22. (UP)\u2014\nWilliam Green, American Federa\ntion of Labor president, today\npledged to American Legionnaires\nthat his organization would resist\nwith all the resources at its com\nmand, communism, fascism, naz\nism and similar movements.\nGreen spoke at the second busi\nness session of the convention at\nwhich 1,339 delegates will receive\nreports from various Legion com\nmittees on Americanism, finance,\nnational defense, child welfare,\nand foreign relations.\nGreen said the agents of sub\nversive forces were assiduously at\nwork attempting to undermine the\nAmerican form of government.\nPARADE LONGEST EVER\nSEEN ON BROADWAY\nNEW YORK, Sept. 22. (UP)\nWith tramping feet and tingling\nmusic, the American Legion gave\nits regards to Broadway and said\nhello to Herald Square yesterday\nwith the longest parade that Fifth\navenue\u2014favorite marching route\nof the nation\u2014ever saw.\nThere may have been 300,000\npersons in the long line that start\ned up the man-made canyon early\nyesterday morning and still was\ntramping past the reviewing stand\nlong after the sun gave up and\ndropped behind the skyscrapers on\nthe edge of the Hudson river. No\nbody could count them.\nA million watched. And there\nwould have been another million\nif police\u2014facing the biggest traf\nfic problem they ever encountered\n\u2014had not turned persons away\nfrom Fifth avenue, explaining that\nit was a mathematical impossibil\nity to pack any more people along\nthe route.\nGO TO SAMARCAND;\nVISIT AT CHAPEL HILL\nMr. and Mrs. Yates Hemphill,\nwho spent the week-end in the\nPiedmont section, the latter hav\ning taken, for the welfare office,\na girl to Samarcand, spent some\ntime at Chapel Hill, where Mr.\nHemphill reported there were\nabout 20 students from Hender\nson county.\nMr. Hemphill stated that he\ntalked with a number of the home\nboys and despite a little homesick\nness all were getting along fine,\nseveral having been successful in\nfinding work to help meet their\nexpenses.\nROOSEVELT IN\nTHREEFOLD\nECONOMY STEP\nReturns Unemployment\nProblem to Local Author\nities as One Phase\nIS LEAVINGTONIGHT\nFOR TOUR TO COAST\nHYDE PAKK, Sept. 22. (UP)\nPresident Roosevelt leaves late\ntoday on his cross-country tour\nto test political sentiment in\nwestern states.\nHe will travel through the\nagrarian northwest where in 1932\nhe smashed Republican bulwarks\nto establish his first New Deal.\nHe will enter the home states\nof liberals who defeated his su\npreme court proposal.\n3 ALPHABETICAL\nAGENCIES ENDED\nBy ARTHUR F. DEGREVE\nUnited Press Staff Correspondent\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 22.\n(UP)\u2014President Roosevelt last\nnight pointed the second New\nDeal toward the triple objective\nof effecting; budget balancing\neconomies, ending priming of the\nbusiness pump with federal dol\nlars and of returning to states\nand cities the financial responsi\nbility of caring for their unenu\nployed.\nThe chief executive partially\ndisclosed his program at Hyde\nPark, Na Y., when he ordered a\nhalt to PWA financing of heavy\nconstruction work, and explained\nthat step was necessitated by\n\"the need to curtail the federal\nbudget\" and defended it as\n\"sound public policy\" since the\n\"passing of the economic emer\ngency\" had placed many commun\nities in an improved financial sta\ntus.\"\nLate Monday Mr. Roosevelt is\nsued an executive order abolish\ning the once all-powerful national\nemergency council on next De\ncember 31. It was formed to co\nordinate the activities of emer\ngency bureaus which sprang into\nlife with startling rapidity and in\ngreat numbers during the hectic\nearly days of the first New Deal.\nOne of those emergency agen\ncies\u2014the Rural Resettlement ad\nministration\u2014recently was merg\ned with the agriculture depart\nment and became known as the\n\"Farm Security administration.\"\nA somewhat brighter financial\npicture faced My. Roosevelt as he\ncarried forward the task of con\noslidating the New Deal. The\ntreasury reported that the federal\ndeficit on September 18 had drop\nped to $284,070,843 the low\nest point since July 7. Likewise\nthe public debt fell below the\n$37,000,000,000 level but remain\ned at a peace-time peak.\nTax collections for the first 18\ndays of the month increased\n$160,000,000 over the same peri\nod last year. The other side of\nthe picture, however, disclosed\nMr. Roosevelt's concern over\nneeded federal economies. The\ntreasury figures showed, in the\nface of business revival, that the\ngovernment on September 18 had\nspent $284,076,843.99 more than\nit received in revenues from all\n(Continued on page six)\nHendersonville and Henderson\ncounty business people \u00bbnd resi\ndents will be urged to co-operate\nin North Carolina Air Mail week,\nOctober 11 to 16, Postmaster E.\nW. Ewbank, a member of the\nstate-wide committee, announced\ntoday.\nThe purpose of the Air Mail\nweek is to bring the attention of\npeople of North Carolina to the\nadvantages of using the air mail\nfacilities of the federal govern\nment, and it is being sponsored\nby the N. C. Association of Post\nmasters with the full co-opera\ntion of Eastern Airlines and the\npostoffice department.\nBeautiful cachets are being pre\npared for every town and city in\nthe state with a landing field,\nand every town in the state with\nan airport will be given full one\nday air mail service. On Octo\nber 12 Eastern Airlines planes\nwill make stops at all cities and\ntowns in the fctate with airports\nand pick up air mail.\nNanking Target of 'Most Merciless' Air Raid\nNanking, above, the ancient capital where China is attempting to rally resistance to the Japanese in\nvasion, is doomed to destruction by Japanese bombs, Nippon's naval commander has announced. The\nmost merciless air attackk of history was predicted. This picture, taken from the Yangtze-Kieng river,\nshows the waterfront of the city, which is regarded as virtually defenseless against air attacks. More\nthan 1,000,000 Chinese live in Nanking. When the bombardment warning wua received there were\nabout 40 Americans, 55 British and 100 Germans there.\nMERCHANTS TO\nOFFER DOLLAR\nDAY BARGAINS\nI\n1 Emphesis Also Will Be\nPlaced on New Fall\nFashions\nWith a tinge of fall in the air,\nHendersonville's annual Dollar\nDays on Friday and Saturday are\nexpected to prove a \"natural\"\nfrom the standpoint of public re\nsponse.\nNot only will prices be slashed\nfor the event, but large emphasis\nwill be placed on style as a fol\nlow-up of fall openings advertis\ned last week in The Times-News.\nAll over the nation people are\ntalking about the appealing new\nfashion trends, and visitors to\nHendersonville stores Friday will,\nfind displayed everything that is\nnew in both men's, women's and\nchildren's wearing apparel in ad\ndition to smaller items of mer\nchandise priced at only $10.\nThursday's edition of The\nTimes-News will be devoted large\nly to Dollar Days advertising, set\nting forth an attractive array of\nmerchandise that wise shoppers\nwill want and need at this time.\nProspective visitors to the stores\nare advised to use the edition as\na guide in planning their shop\nping in order that they may list\ntheir needs and find them easily\nand quickly in the different\nstores.\nPlan To Move First Air Mail At\nHendersonville Port Air Mail Week\nExpect to Celebrate Event as Part of Observance of\nForthcoming State Aii* Mail Week\nUnless present plans are chang\ned, air mail service for Hender\nsonville will be from the Hender\nsonville airport, operated by Os\ncar Meyer, Jr., and located two\nmiles south of the city on the\nSpartanburg road. Postmaster\nEwbank is planning a celebration\nat the field, when officials of the\ntown and county will meet the air\nmail plane. For this reason, every\nresident of the town and county\nwho can do so is urged to prepare J\nair mail for mailing on that day.\nPlans to pick up air mail on\nthat day will start from Kitty\nHawk, where aviation was born\nin this country when the Wright!\nbrothers made their first flight.\nMr. Ewbank is a member of\nthe committee in charge of the\ncelebration. Paul Younts, post\nmaster at Charlotte, is general\nchairman of this committee, and\nWythe Peyton, postmaster at\nAsheville, is president of the Post-.\nmasters' association.\nBRITAIN MAY WITHDRAW HER\nENVOY TO JAPAN AS WARNING\nIN UNRESTRICTED AIR WAR\nBut Final Japanese Reply\nCloses Incident of Shoot\ning Ambassador\nLONDON, Sept. 22.\u2014(UP)\u2014\nGreat Britain today advised Ja\npan that she considered the inci\ndent of the wounding of her am\nbassador, Sir Hutfhe Knatchbull\nHuffessen ended. The announce\nment was made following an ear\nlier statement that Japan's final\nreply in the matter was in transit\ntoday.\nBy RICHARD D. M'MILLAN\nCopyright, 1937, by United Pre\u00ab\nLONDON, Sept. 22. (UP).\u2014It\nwas reported unofficially last\nnight that the British government\nshortly may approach the United\nStates to learn what the reaction\nwould be in Washington if Bri\ntain should withdraw her ambas\nsador from Tokyo.\nThe foreign office would not\ncomment upon the report.\nIt was apparent, however, that\nthe government viewed the Chi\nnese-Japanese situation with in\ncreasing gravity and that Foreign\nSecretary Anthony Eden realized\nthat if Japan carries out her an\nnounced unrestricted aerial\nbombing of Nanking, a final de\ncision on the question of British\nJapanese relations may be neces\nsary.\nWithdrawal of the British am\nbassador, Sir Robert L. Craigie,\nwho has just arrived in the Japa-,\nneso capital, was considered to be\nthe only protest London could\nmake to cause Japan to realize\nthe danger in the trend of events\nshe has forced in Eastern Asia.\nDiplomats said that London is\nattempting to \"cooperate\" close\nly with Washington in the Far\nEast situation and that the Brit-,\nish representations which Ambas\nsador Craigie made to Japanese\nForeign Minister Koki in Tokyo\nyesterday were decided upon only\nafter consultation with the Uni\nted States.\nThe foreign office said that Sir\nRobert referred to the possibility\nthat other than military objec- j\ntives might be hit by Japanese\nbombs (fropped on the Chinese\ncapita] and tnat the lives of Brit\nish citizens might be endangered.\nThe representations were be\nlieved about the same as those J\nmade Monday in Washington by\nSecretary of State Cordell Hull in\nhis talk with the Japanese ambas\nsador. 1\nBritain reserved the right to\nhold the Japanese government re\nsponsible for any damage to Brit\nish lives and property.\nIt was admitted that the repre\nsentations hardly would be ex\npected to produce any important\nresults.\nJapan's reply to the British\nprotest against the shooting of\nthe British ambassador to China,\nSir Hughe Knatchbull-Hugessen,\nallegedly by a Japanese military\nflier, was understood to be en\n(Continued on page six)\nU. S. RUPTURE\nWITH JAPS IS\nTHREATENED\nHull Doing Everything to\nRetain Good Relations\nWith China, Japan\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 22. (UP)\n\u2014The United States has bluntly\nwarned Japan that her proposed\nmass bombing of Nanking, capi\ntal of the Chinese Central govern\nment, would be a violation of in\nternational law and thus would\njeopardize Sino-American diplo\nmatic relations, Secretary of State\nCordell Hull revealed yesterday.\nHull disclosed that vigorous\nrepresentations have been made\nthrough Japanese Ambassador Hi\nrosi Saito here and through Amer\n(Continued on page six)\nCOSTON HEAD\nOF RED CROSS\nLocal Unit Reorganizes;\nStarts Plans for Annual\nRoll Call\nAt a called session of the local\nchapter of the American Red\nCross yesterday, Thos. H. Franks\nresigned as county chairman and\nJ. C. Coston was elected as his\nsuccessor. A. W. Groover also re\nsigned as treasurer and J. H. Rig\ngan was elected to fill this office.\nMrs. Louise Semmes, special\nfield representative of the annual\nroll call division of the Red Cross, j\nwas present and discussed the ap\nproaching membership roll call.\nMr. Franks, in tendering his\nresignation, stated that he had\nserved for about five years and\nvery much to his inconvenience at\ntimes because the busy roll call\nperiod comes at about the same\ntime as the fall term of criminal\ncourt. Mr. Groover had served j\nfor about three years as treasurer\nand felt that some one else should 1\nfill this position.\nMr. Coston will soon appoint\nthe roll call chairman and set up\nthe organization for the roll call\nbefore the annual district meeting\nin Asheville on October 8.\nMrs. Semmes said the member\nship quota for Henderson county\nthis year was 600, which was a\nlittle higher than formerly.\nBOTH CANTON\nAND NANKING\nARE ATTACKED\nAir Raids Coincide With\nGeneral Offensives on\nAll Chinese Fronts\nCHINESE OFFICIALS\nDENOUNCING U. S.\nSHANGHAI, Sept. 22. (UP)\nJapan today loosed the full forco\nof her anger against China in a\nseries of air raids on Nanking and\nCanton. The air raids were timed\nto coincide with the general of\nfensive on all fronts.\nNanking survived the bombings\nwith its spirit high and with little\ndamage.\nUnconfirmed reports from Can\nton said that there were frightful\ncasualties there and severe tires.\nAmericans were in grave dan\nger in the Nanking bombings but\nnone wa* struck.\nFighting around Shanghai\nreached its p6ak of slaughter an\nthe Japanese attack opened.\nFor 18 hours Japanese and Chi\nnese attacked and counter attack\ned in complete disregard of life.\nThe battle was finally stoppud\nbecause they were exhausted.\nIn North China, Japanese\nclaimed big gains.\nReports said grain fields that\nwere ripening a few weeks ago\nare now black with ruin.\n200 CHINESE KILLED\nIN SLUM SECTION\nNANKING, S\u00abpt. 22.\u2014Straw\nhut homes in the slum section of\nthis oity which was twice assault\ned by the Japanese by air today\nburned like tinder and 200 non\ncombatant Chinese were estimat\ned to have befen burned to death\nor wounded. Few residences were\ndestroyed in the better section of\nthe town and Chinese officially\nmaintained that the long expected\nair attack failed to accomplish\nanything of military value.\nEUROPEANS, CHINESE\nSNEER AT AMERICANS\nBr I. J. EPSTEIN\n(Copyright, 1937, United Pre**)\nNANKING, Via Shanghai, Sept.\n22.\u2014(UP)\u2014Anti American sen\ntiment because of the evacuation\nof the United States embassy\nfrom this bomb-threatened capital\nwas increasing today and the\nhandful of United States citizens\nremaining here were subjected to\na series of near-insults.\nAs hours passed following expi\nration of the Japanese zero hour\nfor beginning the \"destruction\"\nof the city by an aerial bombard\nment, the Chinese population was\nincreasingly nervous and the fear\ncomplex exhibited itself in un\nprecedented criticism of the Unit\ned States government and Ameri\ncans generally.\nTfte European communuy nvrtr,\nas wel las the Chinese, was nerv\nous and joined in the sneering\nattitude towards Americans.\nA typical statement was made\nby Mrs. Paul Tyinem, a mission\nary-educator, who gave up Amer\nican citizenship eatfy this year to\nbecome a Chinese.\n\"I yearn for America to recon\nsider her policy,\" Mrs. Tyinem\nsaid. \"I beg her to take positive\nstand for the right and not to\nfear Japan,. The deplorable\nacquiescence of United States\nembassy officials, who have run\naway to a warship in response to\nvirtual demands from Japan, is a\nlast straw causing complete loss\nof respect on the part of innum\nerable Chinese including myself.\"\nChinese officials also continued\ntheir denunciation of the United\nStates, although none would per\nmit himself to be quoted by\nname.\nIndicative of the tension, it\nwas announced yesterday that 77\n\"Chinese traitors\" had been exe\ncuted and that 3,400 nationalist\nstudents from Peiping and Tient\nsin had passed through the city\ndemanding an immediate declara\ntion of war, the extermination of\ntraitors, and the conscription of\nfouth.\nThe personnel of the U. S. em\nbassy and Americans generally\ngnored the anti-American feeling\nind believed that the friendly\nfeeling of Chinese towards them\nwould be restored when the pres\nent tension passes.\nMost of the embassy personnel,\nncluding Ambassador Nelson T.\nfohnson, remained aboard the\ngunboats Luzon and Guam of the\nLJnited States Yangtse river pa\nrol. These ships still were moored\n;o their buoys off the Nanking\nvaterfront last night, despite the\nvarning of the Japanese that for\neign ships should withdraw 12\nniles from Nanking.\nAn embaaay spokesman told\nthe United Press that \"we neither\nintend to aabject ourselves to\nbombing no* to Uare Nanking a\u00ab\nlong as AnMtrlcana remain here.\"","height":"27972","width":"20112"}}
